							<div class="post_wrapper author">
								<div id="about_the_author">
									<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/deborahwilliams/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/dlw-headshot-2024-1-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/dlw-headshot-2024-1-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="Deborah Williams" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
									<div class="description author withsidebar">
										<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/deborahwilliams/">Deborah Williams</a></h6>
										Deborah Williams teaches at New York University. Her scholarly work includes <i>Not in Sisterhood </i>and <i>The Necessity of Young Adult Fiction; </i>and being co-editor of <i>Oxford History of the Novel in English, Volume Eight: US Fiction Since 1940</i>. Various essays of hers have appeared in <i>The New York Times, The Rumpus, The Common</i>, and <i>The Markaz Review, </i>among others. She is currently at work on a novel about Edith Wharton's menopausal reinvention.																			</div>
								</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
							</div>
